			<p>Making automated air-conditioning systems more energy efficient, installing new fluorescent lighting and linking office lights with motion sensors helped UCF save more than $320,000 in energy costs during the first three quarters of the 2008-09&nbsp;fiscal year.</p>
<p>Dave Norvell, director of UCF&rsquo;s Sustainability &amp; Energy Management Department, informed the UCF Board of Trustees of the savings during the board&rsquo;s regular meeting on Thursday. The current fiscal year will conclude June 30.</p>
<p>Norvell described the many ways in which UCF is conserving energy to help the environment and save money. The cost savings are even more critical for the university during tight budget times.</p>
<p>UCF&rsquo;s environmental efforts support President John Hitt&rsquo;s commitment to reduce campus emissions of greenhouse gases. He is a member of the American College &amp; University Presidents Climate Commitment leadership circle. The initiatives that Norvell presented to the Board of Trustees include:</p>
<p>-- Creating a team of UCF employees that specialize in improving the efficiency of heating, ventilation and air-conditioning systems in campus buildings. UCF was the second university in the country to add such a team to its staff.</p>
<p>-- Installing 6,000 fluorescent lights and 1,000 motion sensors to help reduce lighting costs.</p>
<p>-- Continuing an annual competition among UCF residence halls to determine which students can conserve the most energy. Their efforts this year saved the university about $27,000 in energy bills.</p>
<p>-- Constructing new UCF buildings to meet the silver standards of the Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) program, which achieves savings in energy and water consumption.</p>
<p>-- Using solar energy to provide hot water to one of the Towers residence halls and to power a portion of the Engineering I building. Sustainability &amp; Energy Management operates a solar-powered vehicle that has no emissions.</p>
<p>-- Building a new Thermal Energy Storage Facility just east of the Lake Claire community. The&nbsp;storage tank&nbsp;will allow UCF to purchase more electricity during off-peak hours, when it pays a much lower rate, and reduce the costs of cooling campus buildings. The facility should be completed in the fall.</p>
<p>In other action Thursday:</p>
<p>-- The Board of Trustees approved a 15 percent tuition increase, which includes an 8 percent increase in the base tuition and a 7 percent increase known as differential tuition. For undergraduate Florida residents who are taking 30 credit hours a year and paying differential tuition, the annual cost of tuition and fees will increase from $3,947 to $4,526, still among the lowest rates in the country. Differential tuition funds need-based financial aid and undergraduate academic programs. Students who were enrolled as of July 1, 2007, and have been continuously enrolled since that time do not pay differential tuition.</p>
<p>-- Trustees approved UCF&rsquo;s new strategic planning efforts, which will focus the university&rsquo;s role in providing leadership and service to the Central Florida region in the coming years. World-class education, pioneering research and broad-based community service underpin the plan, which provides overarching goals and guidance for all of UCF&rsquo;s academic and administrative units. UCF will engage faculty and staff members, students, alumni and community partners in developing the specific goals and actions of the plan, which is designed to be flexible and responsive to ongoing and emerging requirements.</p>
<p>-- Trustees thanked Central Florida legislators for their support of UCF and the College of Medicine. Legislators who attended and briefly addressed the board were: Sen. Lee Constantine and Reps. Dean Cannon, Dwayne Taylor, Steve Precourt, Scott Randolph, Steve Crisafulli and Mike Horner. The trustees also applauded UCF&rsquo;s Legislative Scholars interns for the spring term: Matthew Benchimol, Katlin Cravatta, Jessica Graham, Michael Lueptow, Lindsey Swindle, Louisa Tarassova and Amanda Williams.</p>
<p>-- UCF welcomed two new trustees. New Faculty Senate Chair Ida Cook and new Student Government Association President Brian Peterson both participated in their first meetings as board members.</p>
<p>-- President Hitt praised UCF researchers for ranking seventh among universities nationwide in the IEEE Spectrum Patents Scorecard. UCF ranked ahead of Princeton, Harvard and the University of North Carolina and was the only Florida university in the top 20. Click <a href="index?page=article&amp;id=00240041339c48b30120a92dbf2f00767d">here</a> to read more.</p>
<p>-- Hitt congratulated the 224 UCF student-athletes who qualified for the Conference USA Commissioner&rsquo;s Honor Roll. UCF surpassed its own conference record of 194 from last year. Click <a href="http://ucfathletics.cstv.com/genrel/041609aaa.html">here</a> to read more.</p>
<p>-- Trustees recognized student-athlete Dione Thomas of the women&rsquo;s track and field team for receiving the 2008-09 Winter Conference USA Spirit of Service award. She was one of 12 athletes recognized for excellence in community service and academics. Click <a href="http://ucfathletics.cstv.com/sports/w-track/spec-rel/040809aaa.html">here</a> to read more.</p>
<p>-- Registrar Dennis Dulniak was recognized for receiving &ldquo;The Founders Award for Leadership&rdquo; from the American Association of Collegiate Registrars and Admissions Officers.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 5th largest in the nation with more than 50,000 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
